{"id":"1003.3602","submitter":"Zurab Silagadze","authors":"Z.K. Silagadze","title":"Sums of generalized harmonic series for kids from five to fifteen","comments":"15 pages, no figures, published version","journal-ref":"Resonance 20N9 (2015), 822-843","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We examine the remarkable connection, first discovered by Beukers, Kolk and\nCalabi, between $\\zeta(2n)$, the value of the Riemann zeta-function at an even\npositive integer, and the volume of some $2n$-dimensional polytope. It can be\nshown that this volume is equal to the trace of a compact self-adjoint\noperator. We provide an explicit expression for the kernel of this operator in\nterms of Euler polynomials. This explicit expression makes it easy to calculate\nthe volume of the polytope and hence $\\zeta(2n)$. In the case of odd positive\nintegers, the expression for the kernel enables us to rediscover an integral\nrepresentation for $\\zeta(2n+1)$, obtained by a different method by\nCvijovi\\'{c} and Klinowski. Finally, we indicate that the origin of the\nmiraculous Beukers-Kolk-Calabi change of variables in the multidimensional\nintegral, which is at the heart of this circle of ideas, can be traced to the\namoeba associated with the certain Laurent polynomial. The paper is dedicated\nto the memory of Vladimir Arnold (1937-2010).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 16 Mar 2010 12:29:52 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 23 Sep 2015 06:13:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-09-24"}
